               <msContents>
                  <summary>Indian reformer <persName key="person_f3663" role="aut"
                        change="#role-assignment">Sayyid Aḥmad K̲h̲ān̲ (1817-189)</persName>
                     composed this work containing a preface, followed by eleven geneological
                     fold-out tables showing the descent and history of the Mughal emperors from
                        <persName type="standard" key="person_63984707"
                        ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/63984707/" role="subject"
                        change="#role-assignment">Tīmūr (b. 1336, r. 1370–1405)</persName> to
                        <persName type="standard" key="person_64248022"
                        ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/64248022/" role="subject"
                        change="#role-assignment">Muhammad Bahadur Shah II, King of Delhi
                        (1775–1862, r. 1837–1857)</persName>, and a conclusion. Seeking to account
                     for less well-known periods of Mughal history in systematic fashion, he spent
                     six months and twenty-five days compiling information from fifteen earlier
                     sources, which he completed for <persName
                        ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9232156619135528780003"
                        key="person_9232156619135528780003">Sir Robert North Collie Hamilton, 6th
                        Baronet (1802–1877)</persName>, then Commissioner at Agra. An unidentified
                     scribe copied this manuscript several years later on <date
                        calendar="#Hijri-qamari" when="1823-10-15">9 Ṣafar 1257 AH (15 Oct.
                        1823)</date>, on behalf of Hindustani poet <persName
                        ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/174703219" key="person_174703219">Ḥātim ʻAlī Mahar
                        (1815–1879)</persName>, who then possibly gave it to <persName
                        type="supplied" key="person_f830" role="fmo" change="#role-assignment"
                        >Colonel George William Hamilton (1807-1868)</persName>.</summary>
